Romanisation of the kana does not always strictly follow the consonant-vowel scheme laid out in the table. For example, ã¡, nominally "ti", is very often romanised as "chi" in an attempt to better represent the actual sound in Japanese.
These basic characters can be modified in various ways. By adding a "dakuten" marker (Â ã‚›), a voiceless consonant is turned into a voiced consonant: "k"â†’"g", "ts/s"â†’"z", "t"â†’"d", "h"â†’"b" and "ch"/"sh"â†’"j". Hiragana beginning with an "h" can also add a "handakuten" marker (Â ã‚œ) changing the "h" to a "p".
